Question 1

The dataset AIS provides an overview of the body composition of athletes across various sports. Created by the Australian Institute of Sport by Telford and Cunningham in 1991, this dataset includes measurements such as height, weight, and other components related to body composition. Additionally, it contains extensive data on the blood composition of the athletes, including HCT (hematocrit), which measures the proportion of red blood cells, and WBC (white blood cell count). This indicates that the study was comprehensive in its data collection about these athletes. The primary goal of the study was to investigate whether differences in blood composition correlate with variations in sports careers.

ais_sm <- AIS %>% 
  filter(Sport %in% c("BBall", 
                      "Rowing", 
                      "Field",
                      "TSprnt")) %>% 
  select(Sport, 
         Sex, 
         contains("B")) %>% 
  arrange(desc(PBF))

Problem 4

Prob_4_Plot <- ggplot(ais_sm, 
        aes(x = RBC, 
            y = WBC, 
            color = Sex)) +
    geom_point(size = 3, 
               alpha = 0.7) +
    geom_smooth(method = "loess", 
                se = FALSE, 
                aes(linetype = Sex)) +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Dark2") +
    labs(title = "Relationship between RBC and WBC Count by Sex",
        x = "Red Blood Cell Count (RBC)",
        y = "White Blood Cell Count (WBC)",
        color = "Sex") +
    theme_minimal() +

Problem 5

wbc_summary <- ais_sm %>%
  group_by(Sex) %>%
  summarize(
    Q1 = quantile(WBC, 0.25),
    Q3 = quantile(WBC, 0.75),
    IQR = Q3 - Q1,
    Lower_Bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR,
    Upper_Bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR,
    Mean = mean(WBC, na.rm = TRUE),
    SD = sd(WBC, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

print(wbc_summary)

The outlier in the dataset appears to be a female participant with extremely lowRBC and WBC values. I created graphs both with and without standard error, and the outlier falls well outside the boundaries for the standard error. This observation suggests that the participant may represent an anomalous case. Looking at the table above, the anomaly significantly deviates from the average figures for both WBC and RBC values when compared to the means for each statistic.
